:::summary
A mathematical proof is a rigorous, step-by-step argument demonstrating that a given statement is necessarily true, given a set of axioms and previously established theorems. Proof is what distinguishes mathematics from all other disciplines — in no other field can we achieve certainty by reasoning alone. For Christians and theologians, mathematical proof has long served as a model for the certainty we can seek in other domains, and the extraordinary power of human reason to discover necessary truths has pointed many thinkers toward the conviction that mathematics is not invented but discovered — that it reflects the order of a rational Creator.
:::

